Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.490 --> 00:00:06.490
[applause]

00:00:06.490 --> 00:00:08.790
&gt;&gt;Dan Roam: Thank you Stephan. I wanna thank
you all for coming. What Stephan said is right

00:00:08.790 --> 00:00:14.230
and it's remarkable to me because as I was
driving down here earlier today I was thinking,

00:00:14.230 --> 00:00:18.970
"My gosh I can't believe that it's actually
been four years since I came to this room

00:00:18.970 --> 00:00:23.560
and gave a talk about my previous book." And
I'm thinking, "From my perspective four years

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:26.689
it's gone by really fast, it doesn't seem
like all that much has happened. I've written

00:00:26.689 --> 00:00:29.980
some more books, I've had a chance to talk
with a lot of people." But then I was thinking,

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:36.030
"My gosh in Google time four years is incredible."
I mean think how much must have changed here.

00:00:36.030 --> 00:00:41.350
So when I came here four years ago I had a
very specific point that I wanted to make

00:00:41.350 --> 00:00:46.620
to people which was that we don't draw enough
and we tend to not think very well because

00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:48.620
we don't use our visual mind very well.

00:00:48.620 --> 00:00:54.489
So my first book was all about solving problems
with pictures and I realize now as the years

00:00:54.489 --> 00:00:59.000
have gone by that a lot of things have changed
in these last four years in terms of helping

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.970
us think visually. There have been a lot of
books that have come out about visual problem

00:01:02.970 --> 00:01:08.670
solving, there's been a lot of interest around
creating applications that people can use

00:01:08.670 --> 00:01:12.810
to help them articulate software that are
more visual, and there's been a whole slew

00:01:12.810 --> 00:01:16.979
of tools that have been released online, many
of them belonging to you, that allow us to

00:01:16.979 --> 00:01:21.369
communicate using pictures a lot more effectively
than we could in the past. But I also realized

00:01:21.369 --> 00:01:23.100
that we're not there yet.

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:27.150
In these last four years we haven't gotten
to the point where we've solved all of our

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:31.200
problems. We still seem to have these challenges
ahead of us and what I really wanted to set

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:36.689
out to do as I was working on this new book
was kind of double down and say, "If my first

00:01:36.689 --> 00:01:40.359
book was just about using pictures, what I
wanna talk with you about today, and what

00:01:40.359 --> 00:01:46.850
my new book is about, is using that combination
of words and pictures to make every idea that

00:01:46.850 --> 00:01:51.940
we have become incredibly clear." Because
I think that the story I'd like to share with

00:01:51.940 --> 00:01:57.249
you is a pretty simple one. As I think about
the ideas that are out there, there are so

00:01:57.249 --> 00:02:01.109
many of them, and we now have so many different
channels by which people communicate their

00:02:01.109 --> 00:02:05.459
ideas to us, it all starts to sound after
a little while like this, just this endless

00:02:05.459 --> 00:02:11.150
wall of words of blah, blah, blah descending
upon us. It's really difficult to begin to

00:02:11.150 --> 00:02:15.690
understand what are the ideas that we really
wanna pursue? What are the things that are

00:02:15.690 --> 00:02:17.780
really interesting to us?

00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:20.890
So what I want to share with you today is
this simple idea of can we move from a world

00:02:20.890 --> 00:02:26.110
that looks like that to a world where maybe
we can start to think about how we can communicate

00:02:26.110 --> 00:02:32.910
our ideas better by using fewer words? We're
still going to use words but we're going to

00:02:32.910 --> 00:02:39.100
help make those words become incredibly powerful
by introducing the idea of combining them

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:40.100
with pictures.

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:43.440
And so I think that the best way to start
out to make this real is I'd like to start

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:47.380
out with kind of two different case studies
of organizations I've worked with over the

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:53.110
last couple of years and they represent kind
of a spectrum to me. On one side an organization

00:02:53.110 --> 00:02:58.550
that has used pictures exceedingly well to
explore really complex ideas and now that's

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:02.650
the good side of the spectrum. And then on
the bad side of the spectrum an organization

00:03:02.650 --> 00:03:05.430
that hasn't used pictures at all and communicates
miserably.

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:09.620
So I'd like to start with the good one. On
the good side, a couple years ago I had a

00:03:09.620 --> 00:03:13.700
chance to go up to Seattle and work with a
number of the program managers that are overseeing

00:03:13.700 --> 00:03:20.130
the development of the new 787, the new Dreamliner,
arguably the most complex machine that has

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:25.010
ever been made. And what they shared with
me is it's even more complex than I had thought

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:31.690
because the 787 is being built at the same
time in 17 different countries by people speaking

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:33.170
13 different languages.

00:03:33.170 --> 00:03:38.760
So for example, the fuselage section in the
front, everything that's in light blue, is

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:43.770
built in the United States. Everything that's
in green, the main fuselage component, is

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:48.930
being built in Italy. Everything that's in
red is being built in Japan; everything that's

00:03:48.930 --> 00:03:52.410
in yellow is being built in China, etcetera.

00:03:52.410 --> 00:03:57.430
So the question I had is how is it possible
for someone in say Shanghai, let's say the

00:03:57.430 --> 00:04:02.190
person who's working on the wing root, to
know how to build their component to within

00:04:02.190 --> 00:04:07.150
tolerances of in some cases millions of an
inch so that it perfectly lines up with the

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:11.180
component being built by someone in Italy
and a component being built by someone in

00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:16.430
Japan? All the pieces get shipped back to
Seattle and they snap together and they fit.

00:04:16.430 --> 00:04:20.370
Well the thing that they showed me up at Seattle
is the reason they're able to that is because

00:04:20.370 --> 00:04:26.440
everything, every aspect of the design, maintenance,
constructions, training, everything that has

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:31.660
to do with that machine is communicated through
pictures; it's as if they've replaced spoken

00:04:31.660 --> 00:04:36.289
language completely. And I'm not just talking
about really sophisticated computer aided

00:04:36.289 --> 00:04:39.470
design. I mean Boeing has had that for decades.

00:04:39.470 --> 00:04:43.710
What is interesting here is the creation of
a global network of a visual language so that

00:04:43.710 --> 00:04:49.449
if have a question about what am I supposed
to do I don't need to read anything, I go

00:04:49.449 --> 00:04:53.219
online, I look at the picture and I see what
I'm supposed to do. And the really remarkable

00:04:53.219 --> 00:04:59.729
thing is that in the end it actually flies;
it works. So that's a really good example,

00:04:59.729 --> 00:05:03.319
that's the good end of the spectrum and I
promised you that I'd show you a bad end of

00:05:03.319 --> 00:05:04.569
the spectrum as well.

00:05:04.569 --> 00:05:08.970
So I wanna talk to you about an organization
where I think communication doesn't work at

00:05:08.970 --> 00:05:13.550
all. Now I have had an opportunity to work
with the United States Senate and a number

00:05:13.550 --> 00:05:18.680
of different governmental organizations. And
the reality is people are incredibly smart,

00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:23.939
people are working very, very hard, but the
problem is that often, because it's all about

00:05:23.939 --> 00:05:28.940
politics, the ideas that this guy is generating
he wants to make absolutely sure that this

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:33.990
guy does not understand. "I wanna make sure
that you don't know what I'm doing, it's secret,

00:05:33.990 --> 00:05:36.800
this is my political agenda." Well that's
part of the problem.

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:40.930
The other problem is that even when those
people agree on what they're trying to do,

00:05:40.930 --> 00:05:47.840
the result of their work looks like that.
Think of how invested you have to be in this

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:52.169
piece of policy or this idea to be willing
to drill all the way down through it to try

00:05:52.169 --> 00:05:57.229
to figure out what it's really about. It doesn't
work, it doesn't fly, and in the end we end

00:05:57.229 --> 00:06:01.990
up with people who become really politically
agitated because they don't know what it is

00:06:01.990 --> 00:06:06.909
that Washington is actually trying to say.
What is the solution? We don't know.

00:06:06.909 --> 00:06:12.660
So what I wanna share with you is something
that is, I think is a tool that can help clarify

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:17.199
this. How do we use the pictures and the words,
put them together? This is something that

00:06:17.199 --> 00:06:23.979
I call vivid thinking. Now vivid is a mnemonic.
Now I am one of those people, my memory just

00:06:23.979 --> 00:06:27.830
sucks, it's not anywhere near as good as it
could be or as I'd like it to be so I rely

00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:31.849
on mnemonics and visual devices all the time
to help me remember things.

00:06:31.849 --> 00:06:41.419
So let me walk you through what vivid actually
stands for. So the V-I stands for visual;

00:06:41.419 --> 00:06:53.020
the V stands for verbal; and the I-D stands
for interdependent. So if we put that together

00:06:53.020 --> 00:07:00.029
what do we have? Visual, verbal, interdependent
thinking. That's the kind of thinking I want

00:07:00.029 --> 00:07:03.069
us to have and then an idea will become truly
vivid.

00:07:03.069 --> 00:07:07.930
Now there's a more vivid way to describe that.
So what it means is I'm no longer going to

00:07:07.930 --> 00:07:12.389
believe that you know what you're talking
about if you can just talk about it. No matter

00:07:12.389 --> 00:07:16.550
how articulate you might be I'm not going
to believe you have fully explored your idea

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:22.300
if you can only talk about it. Nor am I going
to believe that you have fully explored your

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:25.960
idea if you can only draw it.

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:30.680
Vivid thinking means that we will combine
both. And for some neurobiological reasons

00:07:30.680 --> 00:07:34.970
that we'll talk about in a few minutes this
is the really critical factor. When we want

00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:40.439
out mind to light up on an idea, when we have
an idea and we wanna share it with someone,

00:07:40.439 --> 00:07:45.680
when we combine words and pictures, which
most of us have never been taught to do, it's

00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:50.090
almost magic that happens the way it lights
up other people's minds and our own.

00:07:50.090 --> 00:07:54.629
So what vivid thinking really is, for anybody
who has an opportunity to look through my

00:07:54.629 --> 00:07:59.720
book, vivid thinking in the end of the day
is a very simple set of tools that since most

00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:03.741
of us believe we are primarily verbal and
that's what we've been taught in school, so

00:08:03.741 --> 00:08:09.180
our default thinking process for most of us
involves writing or speaking. What vivid does

00:08:09.180 --> 00:08:14.340
is it gives us a very simple set of tools
to overlay on top of those words and say,

00:08:14.340 --> 00:08:21.629
"If I had to create a visual to compliment
those words what would I do? Because I don't

00:08:21.629 --> 00:08:26.990
know how to draw." It tells us, vivid thinking
tells us exactly how to do that.

00:08:26.990 --> 00:08:32.070
The reason why this works, there are a couple
of unwritten rules about visual problem solving

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:36.570
and vivid problem solving. And I wanna share
with you the most important one goes like

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:44.550
this: whoever best describes the problem is
the person most likely to solve the problem.

00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:48.710
Now what I mean by that is if any of you are
in a position to assign budgets or to assign

00:08:48.710 --> 00:08:51.960
work to others, and I'm assuming many of you
are, if someone came running into your room

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:56.360
and said, "Give me money, the sky is falling,
I'll fix it," you're probably gonna say, "Not

00:08:56.360 --> 00:09:01.399
so fast." But if the person came in and said,
"Look I've started to map out the problem

00:09:01.399 --> 00:09:07.209
and I've realized that when these people or
these constituents get together in this way

00:09:07.209 --> 00:09:12.709
there seems to be a series of consistent outcomes
and what I'd like to do is explore why this

00:09:12.709 --> 00:09:16.029
one always goes badly. Could you give me some
more money to explore it?"

00:09:16.029 --> 00:09:22.230
The fact is the person who has already begun
to map out the problem is the person who proves

00:09:22.230 --> 00:09:27.250
that they have the greatest grasp of it and
also is beginning to find what the solution

00:09:27.250 --> 00:09:33.070
is likely to be. So the really mercenary subtext
here, and this is true, is whoever draws the

00:09:33.070 --> 00:09:37.720
best picture gets the funding; absolutely
true rule number one, whoever draws he best

00:09:37.720 --> 00:09:42.670
picture gets the funding. We don't see this
rule very often because we don't draw very

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:47.520
often, but every time somebody does they win.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:52.360
And I wanna show you the best example of this
ever, the best sort of back of the napkin,

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:57.230
simple, visual idea ever. So we're out here
in the Bay Area, let's fly out here to Washington,

00:09:57.230 --> 00:10:01.171
'cause as I've mentioned I had chance to work
with the Senate and the U.S. Navy, and some

00:10:01.171 --> 00:10:03.500
other organizations in D.C.

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:08.660
And after one of my talks a guy came up to
me who was head of the new policy for the

00:10:08.660 --> 00:10:12.880
United States Senate for the Democratic side
of the Senate, and he said, "Dan, I have the

00:10:12.880 --> 00:10:17.540
perfect, simple picture back of the napkin
story for you from politics." And he shared

00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:23.560
this picture and it goes back to 1974, so
we're talking kind of ancient history now,

00:10:23.560 --> 00:10:28.250
when Ford, President Ford was in power.

00:10:28.250 --> 00:10:33.569
President Ford ran a very conservative, fiscally
conservative administration. There was a very

00:10:33.569 --> 00:10:41.810
popular economist at that time, his name was
Arthur Laffer, USC economist, very conservative

00:10:41.810 --> 00:10:47.000
in his views, who spent a lot of time in D.C.
doing consulting for the Ford Administration.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:53.020
So one night Arthur Laffer goes out to a bar
with two senior aides to President Ford, they

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:58.180
go to a bar in Washington D.C. and they start
talking about taxation and monetary policy.

00:10:58.180 --> 00:11:02.170
And at one point Laffer pulls out the cocktail
napkin and he says, "Guys I have an idea.

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:06.220
Do you mind if I draw a little picture for
you?" And the two guys he's with said, "No,

00:11:06.220 --> 00:11:12.360
no go ahead." So on his napkin Laffer draws
a very simple little x, y plot, something

00:11:12.360 --> 00:11:16.649
I'm sure all of us have done at one time or
another, and since they're talking about taxation

00:11:16.649 --> 00:11:23.209
on the horizontal axis he maps out the percent
tax rate that the government is charging on

00:11:23.209 --> 00:11:30.240
our income from zero percent up to one hundred
percent. And on the vertical scale he maps

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:35.790
out how much money does the government actually
collect in tax revenue from zero dollars up

00:11:35.790 --> 00:11:40.190
to lots and lots of dollars. And he says to
the guys that are there in the bar with him

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:45.410
on this napkin he says, "Okay so if the government
charges us zero percent income tax how much

00:11:45.410 --> 00:11:51.199
is the government going to make? Zero." And
then he said, "But think about this: if the

00:11:51.199 --> 00:11:56.030
government charges us one hundred percent
income tax, how much money is the government

00:11:56.030 --> 00:12:00.540
going to make? Also zero because no one will
work."

00:12:00.540 --> 00:12:06.259
Think about that, if every single penny of
every dime of every dollar that you earn came

00:12:06.259 --> 00:12:10.450
in one pocket and you immediately had to pay
all of it back out in income tax, what would

00:12:10.450 --> 00:12:13.220
be the point of even working? You might as
well just forget about it, just go to the

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:14.220
beach.

00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:18.610
So he drew on his napkin what actually seems
to happen is there must be some kind of a

00:12:18.610 --> 00:12:24.720
curve that goes like that. And at some point
isn't it interesting that reducing the rate

00:12:24.720 --> 00:12:30.269
of taxation actually increases the amount
of money the government collects?

00:12:30.269 --> 00:12:34.029
Now the two guys who were with Laffer that
night in the bar thought that was pretty interesting;

00:12:34.029 --> 00:12:37.550
these are the two guys. They said, "Can we
take that napkin back to show it to President

00:12:37.550 --> 00:12:43.360
Ford? There is a fundamentally interesting
idea in that drawing." He said, "Please take

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:44.360
the napkin."

00:12:44.360 --> 00:12:47.111
They took and they showed it to President
Ford who was very intrigued by the idea, he

00:12:47.111 --> 00:12:52.160
got it, he liked it. Ford passed that napkin
off to the Republican National Committee,

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:57.660
who then passed that napkin off to the economics
team of a guy named Ronald Reagan who was

00:12:57.660 --> 00:13:02.990
thinking of running for President. And quite
literally that napkin sketch became the basis

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:04.110
of Reaganomics.

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:08.440
That is the first instance anywhere in the
public record of anybody ever talking about

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:12.959
what became known as supply side economics.
The idea, when someone would come to President

00:13:12.959 --> 00:13:18.540
Reagan and they'd say, "Wait a minute in order
to increase taxable revenue, government revenue,

00:13:18.540 --> 00:13:22.920
you're gonna decrease the rate of taxation
especially for the wealthy? What?" He would

00:13:22.920 --> 00:13:25.810
draw them out that picture and they'd say,
"Oh, I get it."

00:13:25.810 --> 00:13:29.170
Now the interesting part about this story
is the two guys who were with Arthur Laffer

00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:35.360
that night in the bar are these two guys:
Former Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:39.350
and Former Vice President Dick Cheney were
the two guys who were sitting in the bar that

00:13:39.350 --> 00:13:44.820
night with Arthur Laffer. It was those three
guys with that cocktail napkin who basically

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:50.839
invented Reaganomics that night in that bar.
That became pretty much underlying American

00:13:50.839 --> 00:13:56.129
economic policy for most of the last 30 years
and we are still debating to this day is it

00:13:56.129 --> 00:13:57.560
a good idea or not?

00:13:57.560 --> 00:14:01.819
But here's the question I have: who says a
simple little sketch on the back of napkin

00:14:01.819 --> 00:14:07.330
doesn't have power? It has extraordinary power.
That's what I was referring to when I was

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:12.370
saying, "Whoever draws the best picture gets
the funding." The person who comes up with

00:14:12.370 --> 00:14:22.449
the visual clarity of their idea always wins
for a very simple reason. We are of two minds,

00:14:22.449 --> 00:14:27.209
and I am not talking about left brain and
right brain thinking. Everybody's familiar

00:14:27.209 --> 00:14:30.819
with the idea of right brain and left brain
thinking; one of our hemispheres is creative

00:14:30.819 --> 00:14:34.639
and one's analytical. No, it is nowhere near
that simple.

00:14:34.639 --> 00:14:40.879
Now one thing we do know is that all, the
brains of all mammals, all mammal brains,

00:14:40.879 --> 00:14:44.810
have a bilobed neocortex, the part on the
top of the brain is split in half. But as

00:14:44.810 --> 00:14:50.721
far as we can tell right now, to the limit
that tests allow at this point, humans seem

00:14:50.721 --> 00:14:55.899
to be the only mammal in which it is true
the two hemispheres have evolved to have slightly

00:14:55.899 --> 00:15:00.439
different function. And now we are beginning
to realize what the difference between the

00:15:00.439 --> 00:15:05.230
two hemispheres of our brain really is and
it boils down to something like this: one

00:15:05.230 --> 00:15:11.459
half of our brain has evolved to become really
good at looking at the world in terms of little

00:15:11.459 --> 00:15:18.069
bits, pixels, little bits of focus. The other
half of our brain has evolved to become really

00:15:18.069 --> 00:15:21.310
good at being the glue that pulls them back
altogether.

00:15:21.310 --> 00:15:25.790
So there's another way of looking at this
that says, "This part of our brain has evolved

00:15:25.790 --> 00:15:31.029
to be really good at focus." Somewhere in
our evolutionary past it was very important

00:15:31.029 --> 00:15:36.040
for us to be able to scan the horizon and
see the one thing that we wanted to go get.

00:15:36.040 --> 00:15:40.480
But if we only focus on that we're gonna be
attacked by something from behind us. So the

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:46.160
other half of our brain evolves to be really
good at peripheral vision. Pretty fascinating

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:49.910
what we're starting to find is that half our
brain is really good at the focus and the

00:15:49.910 --> 00:15:54.550
other half is good at the larger picture.
That's what we know.

00:15:54.550 --> 00:16:00.459
Another way to think about this, the way this
has further evolved, one way to diagram this

00:16:00.459 --> 00:16:06.300
out, looks something like this. One half of
our brain does want to see the world like

00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:12.370
that, little bits, letters, words, can I break
it down to its elemental pieces? The other

00:16:12.370 --> 00:16:17.810
part of our brain wants to say, "That's not
what it's about. It's about the whole thing."

00:16:17.810 --> 00:16:22.209
Now what's interesting is both of these are
the same and yet of course both of these are

00:16:22.209 --> 00:16:29.319
completely different. Which one is right?
Is this the right description or is this the

00:16:29.319 --> 00:16:31.220
right description?

00:16:31.220 --> 00:16:35.790
Well the answer of course is that both of
them are the right description, but this is

00:16:35.790 --> 00:16:42.900
the only one that for most of us in most of
our education we are ever taught to develop.

